<h2>Winning the hearts of the people through propaganda</h2>
<h4>During WWII, when Hitler was in power and Joseph Goebbels was chief of propaganda, propaganda for Hitler and his way of controlling and ruling spiked. On top of there being posters everywhere supporting Hitler and throwing the Jews under the bus, the Germans took an extra step, to get rid of all the books that they didn’t like the ideas of them. Many books were burned because they were inspirational and thought of turning against the government if the reader didn’t like how things were done. They also were burned because their writers were Jewish. Another reason they were burned is because the books showed different beliefs than the Germans believed so the Germans got rid of them. The article Nazi Propaganda and Censorship states “On that night more than 25,000 books were burned. Some were works of Jewish writers, including Albert Einstein and Sigmund Freud. Most of the books were by non-Jewish writers, including such famous Americans as Jack London, Ernest Hemingway, and Sinclair Lewis, whose ideas the Nazis viewed as different from their own and therefore not to be read” This article also talks about how new textbooks were written by the Germans. These textbooks included obedience for the party and love for Hitler. Everywhere, people were celebrating Hitler’s birthday and the date he came to power. Even after school groups taught about being faithful to Hitler and their country. As you can see, during WWII, Germany was in a total dictatorship because of how much hitler controlled everything people read, said and celebrated.
<br>
<br>
The source, Description of Nazi Propaganda Themes, is about how the Nazi’s used propoganda to convince the people that their truth is the right truth. First of all, they “Made a Leader” and “Rallied the Nation.” “Making a leader” basically meant that they gave the revolution a face, Hitler, and “Rallying the Nation” basically meant that they got everyone on their side and their goal was well known. The next two steps were “Defining the Enemy” and “Indoctrinating Youth.” “Defining the Enemy” was when they went against the Jews to make Germany have a clear goal, and “Indoctrinating Youth” was the purpose of Hitler Youth so that the next generation of Germany would grow up with Hitler’s ideals and carry on Germany when the first generation passed. FInally, the last three steps were “Writing the News,” “Deceiving the Public,” and “Assessing Guilt.” They wrote the news so that their propaganda would be interpreted as truth, this linked with deceiving the public so that the public thinks that their best interests are being taken into consideration, when in reality, it is only the dictator’s best interests, and, at the end, they assessed guilt and saw the error in their ways. Overall, this source highlighted the steps that Germany took with their propaganda and their propaganda themes.
<br>
<br>
The rise of Nazi Germany was greatly influenced by the hard times after WWI. To start, Propaganda becomes the central tool to convince the mass of people to join and support the nazi. It was displayed when the Nazi party was created Hitler had Joseph Goebbels as the head of the ministry of propaganda. The ministry of propaganda basically had control over the hole media, which includes, art, music, films, books, and the radio. Finally, Hitler also thought that speeches was a big part of propaganda. He would plan every signal emotion he would use. Nazi Germany uses propaganda that will increase general moral and the support for the Nazi.
</h4>
